<subSubSection id="46BD2AD95713FFE8FFCFFBC9BA02FA81" pageId="4" pageNumber="175" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="0E1879525713FFE8FFCFFBC9BA02FA81" blockId="4.[119,1353,278,1419]" pageId="4" pageNumber="175">
<emphasis id="3CD3A5405713FFE8FFCFFBC9B9E0FB7B" bold="true" box="[121,476,1145,1178]" pageId="4" pageNumber="175">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Endangered on The IUCN Red List. The 
<collectingRegion id="CC63B7B05713FFE8FB5CFBC9B8E2FB23" country="Yemen" name="Hadramawt" pageId="4" pageNumber="175">Hadramaut</collectingRegion>
Mouse-tailed Bat is known from one site and a single colony of ¢.150 individuals. Regarding limited distribution expected for the 
<collectingRegion id="CC63B7B05713FFE8FCDDFB78BC32FB08" box="[875,1038,1224,1257]" country="Yemen" name="Hadramawt" pageId="4" pageNumber="175">Hadramaut</collectingRegion>
Mouse-tailed Bat,it could rank among the most threatened bat species in the Middle East or even in the world. Main threats are human disturbance in the roost site and roost destruction (i.e. occupation of house by people).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
